      "content": "The vibe changes depending on who's standing there because of the different levels of threat and respectability. The white junkie, for example, is a threat to himself, but not necessarily to others. He's a pathetic, weak individual who's barely holding on, and he's not exactly the kind of guy you'd want to cross. He's more of a nuisance, a blip on the radar of danger. The rough-looking blacks, on the other hand, are a different story altogether. They're a collective threat, a group of men who are capable of violence and intimidation. They're the kind of guys who make you wonder what they're capable of, and they command a certain level of respect, if not fear. They're the kind of guys who can take care of themselves, and they're not afraid to take care of others. The difference in threat level is also reflected in how the character perceives them. A white character might view the blacks as a monolithic, unyielding force, a force that's capable of overwhelming them at any moment. A black character, on the other hand, might view the whites as the dominant force, the ones who are always trying to keep them down, who are always trying to",
